1. Tokenize a paragraph
Take a short paragraph (3–4 sentences) in your language (e.g., from news, a story, or social media).

My Paragraph:
I can’t attend the meeting today, but I’ll send the notes tonight. NLP feels challenging at first, yet it’s very practical in real systems. People don’t notice how much punctuation and contractions affect tokenization.

•	Do naïve space-based tokenization.

      Naïve space-based tokenization splits text into tokens using the whitespaces (space, tabs, newlines) in the given sentence.
      
      If I do text.split(), the result will be like - 
      ['I', 'can’t', 'attend', 'the', 'meeting', 'today,', 'but', 'I’ll', 'send', 'the', 'notes', 'tonight.',
      'NLP', 'feels', 'challenging', 'at', 'first,', 'yet', 'it’s', 'very', 'practical', 'in', 'real', 'systems.',
      'People', 'don’t', 'notice', 'how', 'much', 'punctuation', 'and', 'contractions', 'affect',
      'tokenization.']

•	Manually correct the tokens by handling punctuation, suffixes, and clitics.
Submit both versions and highlight differences.

As we know that punctuations and special characters can be considered as separate tokens, and Naïve space based tokenization is failing to tokenize them

Manual tokenization

      ['I', 'can', "n't", 'attend', 'the', 'meeting', 'today', ',', 'but', 'I', "'ll", 'send', 'the', 'notes', 'tonight', '.',
      'NLP', 'feels', 'challenging', 'at', 'first', ',', 'yet', 'it', "'s", 'very', 'practical', 'in', 'real', 'systems', '.',
      'People', 'do', "n't", 'notice', 'how', 'much', 'punctuation', 'and', 'contractions', 'affect',
      'tokenization', '.']
      
      What I corrected :
        •	today, → today + ,
        •	tonight. → tonight + .
        •	I’ll → I + 'll
        •	it’s → it + 's
        •	can’t → can + n't
        •	don’t → do + n't  

2. Compare with a Tool
Run the paragraph through an NLP tool that supports your language (e.g., NLTK, spaCy, or any open-source tokenizer if available).
•	Compare tool output vs. your manual tokens.
    
    If I tokenize using NLTK word_tokenize, it will be very close to my manual tokens, but there is a common difference for “can’t”:
    •	My manual choice: can + n't
    •	NLTK style (Penn Treebank style): ca + n't
    
    So NLTK often outputs:
      ['I', 'ca', "n't", 'attend', 'the', 'meeting','today',
      ',', 'but', 'I', "'ll",'send', 'the', 'notes', 'tonight', '.','NLP', 'feels', 'challenging', 'at', 'first', ',', 'yet', 'it', "'s", 'very','practical', 'in', 'real', 'systems', '.','People', 'do', "n't", 'notice', 'how', 'much', 'punctuation', 'and','contractions', 'affect', 'tokenization', '.']
      
• Which tokens differ? Why?

      Tokens differ in NLTK-style details:
        •	can’t → ca + n't
        •	I’ll → I + 'll
        •	it’s → it + 's
        •	don’t → do + n't
      
      Why this difference happens (simple):
      NLTK follows a standard tokenization convention (Penn Treebank) where "can't" is represented as "ca" + "n't". It looks odd, but it’s used for consistency in NLP datasets and models.

3. Multiword Expressions (MWEs)
Identify at least 3 multiword expressions (MWEs) in your language. Example:
•	Place names, idioms, or common fixed phrases.
•	Explain why they should be treated as single tokens.
     
      3 MWEs from my paragraph (word groups that behave like one meaning chunk):
        1.	real systems (refers to practical applications, not “systems” in general)
        2.	at first (a fixed phrase meaning “initially”)
        3.	send the notes (common phrase expressing one action)
      
      Why MWEs matter:
      If we treat these as totally separate words, some meaning can get weaker. For example, “at” and “first” individually don’t clearly mean “initially” unless we keep them together as a phrase.

4. Reflection (5–6 sentences)
•	What was the hardest part of tokenization in your language?
•	How does it compare with tokenization in English?
•	Do punctuation, morphology, and MWEs make tokenization more difficult?
      
      Tokenization is harder than it seems because punctuation and contractions create many special cases. When I used naive space splitting, commas and periods stayed attached to words, which makes word counting and modeling messy. Manual tokenization was cleaner because I separated punctuation and split contractions like don’t and it’s into smaller parts. A tool like NLTK handles many of these rules automatically and produces consistent results. However, tokenizers can still differ based on their conventions, like NLTK splitting “can’t” as ca + n't instead of can + n't. Also, MWEs show that meaning is not always in single words—sometimes a phrase acts like one unit.
